This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring September 17, 2015, as Constitution Day and Citizenship Day, and September 17 through September 23, 2015, as Constitution Week. The proclamation emphasizes the significance of the Constitution as a roadmap for citizenship and a framework for democracy. It also highlights the belief that being a citizen is about more than circumstances of birth, but also about shared beliefs, unalienable rights, and obligations to one another and future generations. The proclamation encourages ceremonies and programs to reflect on the importance of active citizenship, recognize the strength of the Constitution, and reaffirm commitment to the rights and obligations of citizenship in the United States.